00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:35.430 position:72%
One of the things that we want to kind of give
a bit more context to this idea of working

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:38.590
with young children in the
use of primary sources.

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:41.020 position:69%
When we're really looking at young children,

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:47.600 position:67%
we recognize that young children already
have great familiarity with gaining meaning

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:50.000 position:59%
about the real world through pictures.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:57.260 position:67%
In fact, even toddlers have been shown that
they can transfer novel information taken

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:02.710 position:56%
from realistic images and apply that
to their emerging world knowledge.

00:06:02.710 --> 00:06:05.570 position:66%
So, one of the things we've been exploring

00:06:05.570 --> 00:06:12.630 position:69%
in our own research is how historical images
can provide a conduit for young children

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:20.130 position:73%
to use their real world experiences and prior
knowledge and then learn how to make inferences

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:25.800 position:56%
about time and place and expand
their understanding of key concepts.

00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:32.480 position:72%
So, we are working with teachers on how they
can build upon this pictorial competence young

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:38.280 position:72%
children already have as it gradually
develops over time throughout the early years.

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:42.830
But the issue that we need
to face is that teachers need

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:48.670 position:63%
to intentionally expand upon young
children's access to informational text.

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:52.160
And this, unfortunately,
tends to be marginalized

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:55.130 position:56%
in most early learning environments.

00:06:55.130 --> 00:07:01.430 position:67%
In fact, research shows that in the typical
first grade classroom, children spend less

00:07:01.430 --> 00:07:06.120
than three minutes a day
with informational texts.

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:09.410
So, our first point of access
is how we can bring

00:07:09.410 --> 00:07:13.260 position:69%
into the classroom these valuable resources.

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:18.450
We know that within our early
childhood classrooms

00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:24.460
that there already is a privileged
positions of text based literacies.

00:07:24.460 --> 00:07:30.860
Literacy forms the core of most
early childhood curriculum.

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:36.630 position:64%
And, although text does occupy this
privileged position in classrooms, we do,

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:40.050
as we've already said, see
that visual representations

00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:43.710 position:69%
of knowledge are a key role for early years.

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:50.450 position:66%
And so we're looking at how we can draw on
developmentally appropriate accommodations

00:07:50.450 --> 00:07:54.140
to bring in visual images
as part of communication.

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:59.780 position:69%
In fact, teachers already do this inherently
and naturally as part of their practices.

00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:05.940 position:75%
We often times will scaffold children's
learning experiences or encourage them to engage

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:11.260 position:61%
in multimodal expressions with pictures
or accompany their written words

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:13.570
and verbal responses with drawings.

00:08:13.570 --> 00:08:17.260 position:63%
Unfortunately, though, many of us are --

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:24.740 position:72%
have to negotiate our way with curriculum
that often situates these images as incidental

00:08:24.740 --> 00:08:30.250 position:64%
and we don't fully appreciate necessarily
the intellectual sophistication

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:37.820 position:72%
that these images provide that does even rival
text based literacies for young learners.

00:08:39.550 --> 00:08:45.280 position:61%
So, here, in this image here, we have
depicted a reading lesson taking place.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:49.370 position:73%
A very familiar, sort of iconic representation.

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:53.180
And we know, although we've
already said, the inherent value

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:57.890
that primary sources can have
as an instructional resources.

00:08:57.890 --> 00:09:05.390 position:64%
Most early childhood and early elementary
teachers have not had formal preparation

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:10.580 position:61%
or professional development that guides
them in how to bring these resources

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:16.160 position:70%
into their classrooms and work with young
learners in ways that would be able to access

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:19.360 position:56%
and engage their funds of knowledge.

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:24.130 position:63%
Moreover, because we've had such limited
research up to this point in time

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:29.880 position:64%
on the integration of primary sources and
the early grades, a lot of the research

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:36.020 position:72%
that people have had to rely on have really be
situated more for how to use this instruction

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:38.950
with students and intermediate
grades and higher.

00:09:38.950 --> 00:09:43.070 position:72%
And we cannot just take those prophecies meant

00:09:43.070 --> 00:09:46.950
for older learners and extrapolate
them downward.

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:51.530 position:64%
Young children have their own unique ways
of knowing and wisdom about the world.

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:58.050 position:66%
And so we want to be able to connect into
those valuable ways that they think about.

00:09:58.050 --> 00:10:04.360 position:72%
Even though we've had these challenges, we
also do have an opportunity and an entry point

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:11.020 position:75%
because most states throughout the United States
have standards that require the introduction

00:10:11.020 --> 00:10:16.100
and use of primary sources
beginning as early as kindergarten.

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:20.370
And so that's our entry point for
us to be able to look for ways

00:10:20.370 --> 00:10:25.090 position:63%
that we can bring them into our classes.

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:28.370 position:59%
So, what do we mean by developmentally
appropriate practice?

00:10:28.370 --> 00:10:33.640 position:64%
Well, what we're talking about there is
the ways that we can connect specifically

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:38.210
with young learners ways of making
sense and meaning of the world.

00:10:38.210 --> 00:10:45.560 position:69%
We recognize, as this young child is showing
us here, that curiosity ignites discovery.

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:52.100 position:73%
When we unveil a sort of a -- begin asking
brilliant amazing sort of questions of interest

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:57.620 position:73%
about things that we see in front of us, that
-- and these initiates our process of discovery

00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:01.470 position:58%
and inquiry that young learners
actually have an inherent skill with.

00:11:01.470 --> 00:11:05.650 position:61%
In fact, they're very skilled at asking
us the most embarrassing questions

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:07.050
at the least opportune time.

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:13.040 position:58%
But we also recognize that this
process of seeing, of what's in front

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:18.820 position:61%
of you comes well before even the words
and the vocabulary have developed.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:24.840 position:63%
Children look and they recognize before
they even have the capability of speech.

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:30.250
And so because this visual
literacy precedes verbal fluency,

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:35.860 position:58%
this is a very important foundation
for early reading and writing skills.

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:41.870 position:66%
But in order for those visual images to
maximize student learning and achievement,

00:11:41.870 --> 00:11:47.180
teachers need to include techniques
for teaching children visually.

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:53.710 position:70%
So, this involves an intentional exploration
of images as part of this pedagogy in schools

00:11:53.710 --> 00:11:59.010 position:61%
that we move students from what we
refer to as sort of an arbitrary seeing

00:11:59.010 --> 00:12:03.460 position:61%
where there's not a lot of sense making
or exploration or deep consideration

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:08.230
about what's there to moving them
more to a deliberate looking.

00:12:08.230 --> 00:12:14.050 position:67%
And that deliberate looking begins to
problematize images as we construct meaning

00:12:14.050 --> 00:12:19.910
of information that's depicted
in visual data in front of us.

00:12:21.290 --> 00:12:25.210
So, we're going to share
with you lessons learned

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:28.870
from actual implementation
that's been done in classrooms

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:32.180 position:59%
from preschool up through grade three.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:38.140 position:70%
And these are the field based lessons that we
have learned from our teachers and children

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:43.040
with whom we've worked that have
informed our body of research.

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:50.420 position:66%
So, one of the things that we recognize
is that teachers initially face challenges

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:56.370 position:58%
when they are searching for
developmentally appropriate resources

00:12:56.370 --> 00:12:59.800
to introduce to young students.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:05.230 position:70%
So, one of the things that happens is that in
order for a primary source to be meaningful,

00:13:05.230 --> 00:13:10.630 position:64%
we recognize that our young learners need
to be able to engage with it personally.

00:13:10.630 --> 00:13:15.150
So, there has to be something
about it that has some familiarity.

00:13:15.150 --> 00:13:19.990 position:58%
And it's on that personal connection,
that relevance and familiarity,

00:13:19.990 --> 00:13:24.500
on which they can find initial
pleasure in looking at it,

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:30.590 position:64%
feel interest in what they're looking at,
and then also begin exploring alternative

00:13:30.590 --> 00:13:35.640
or deeper meanings that can expand
their intellectual engagement

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:39.110 position:75%
and really foster their exploration of concepts.

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:44.030
So, given that, not all images are
well suited for young children.

00:13:44.030 --> 00:13:49.030
The other thing is that teachers
also have some challenges

00:13:49.030 --> 00:13:52.880 position:67%
with are navigating the archives themselves

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:56.200
to locate developmentally
appropriate and relevant images.

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:02.090 position:64%
And that can be frustrating sometimes
because the archives themselves can prove

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:06.400
to be a bit cumbersome if you don't
know the exact words to put in

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:11.530 position:58%
or not necessarily even using words
that fit within a historical context.

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:18.030 position:73%
So, for example, a teacher may put in the words
"grocery store," but in the historical context

00:14:18.030 --> 00:14:23.650 position:73%
