of our teachers lack the content
knowledge related to the images

00:18:33.430 --> 00:18:36.660
that they might be exploring
with their young learners.

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:40.730 position:56%
In this particular case, we're going

00:18:40.730 --> 00:18:44.130
to be showing you an image of
what's called a White Wing.

00:18:44.130 --> 00:18:49.090 position:56%
And when you look at this individual
and you simply look at the caption,

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:51.230 position:58%
you might not get enough information.

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:54.350 position:61%
So, teachers, again, and their
students might struggle to make meaning

00:18:54.350 --> 00:18:56.330 position:61%
of what's incorporated into this image.

00:18:56.330 --> 00:18:58.150
So, how do we go about doing that?

00:18:58.150 --> 00:19:01.500
We have to ask questions.

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:04.710
For example, who are the
helpers in our neighborhood?

00:19:04.710 --> 00:19:07.580
Who were the helpers long ago?

00:19:07.580 --> 00:19:10.090
Let's do some research.

00:19:10.090 --> 00:19:14.160 position:66%
So, when we look at this picture, let's
play a game of hide and seek for a second.

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:16.860 position:59%
Can anyone see the pig in the picture?

00:19:16.860 --> 00:19:20.000
Where's the pig located?

00:19:25.050 --> 00:19:28.120
So, you can see the pig on the
left hand side in the corner.

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:31.520 position:63%
And you might ask yourself, "Why is
something like that important especially

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:35.150
when you just showed us a picture
of a man sweeping the street?"

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:39.570
Well, pigs were used in New
York City to clean up trash.

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:44.840 position:61%
But the pigs themselves often made more
of a mess than they were cleaning up.

00:19:44.840 --> 00:19:50.650 position:69%
So, as a researcher with your young children
in class, you can explore these discussions

00:19:50.650 --> 00:19:55.260
about what was New York City
like, who were these white wings?

00:19:55.260 --> 00:19:58.370
And what was their job?

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:04.070 position:72%
These individuals would play an important role
in the health and wellbeing of New York City.

00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:05.030
And it's interesting.

00:20:05.030 --> 00:20:06.150
They were called white wings.

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:10.100 position:56%
And, you know, when you think of the
image of white and nice and clean,

00:20:10.100 --> 00:20:11.000 position:58%
they were there to clean up the city.

00:20:14.310 --> 00:20:21.310 position:73%
Now, one of the interesting elements associated
with cleaning up the city is going beyond that,

00:20:21.310 --> 00:20:26.690 position:56%
taking a look at how pigs were used,
what life was like in New York City.

00:20:26.690 --> 00:20:31.490 position:73%
And there are a number of images
incorporated into the primary source collection

00:20:31.490 --> 00:20:34.840
at the Library of Congress that
you can explore in greater detail.

00:20:34.840 --> 00:20:40.040 position:58%
Or you could even watch films
related to the white wings on parade.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:45.350 position:70%
And this creates a great frame of reference
for our young learners when they actually get

00:20:45.350 --> 00:20:47.540
to see the white wings in action.

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:54.970 position:70%
But when you look at these large pictures
and you help your students contain themselves

00:20:54.970 --> 00:20:59.300 position:59%
as they look at all of these different
images and they try to explore all

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:03.000
of the different representations
in an image, where do they focus?

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.470
How do you help them focus?

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:09.910 position:61%
One of the great ways that is available
is something called the crop-it.

00:21:09.910 --> 00:21:12.960
The crop-it technique is something
that you may or may not be familiar

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:15.160 position:63%
with where you take two pieces of paper.

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:17.530 position:66%
You can do it either digitally or by hand.

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:21.690
And you can zoom into a particular
element in a photo.

00:21:21.690 --> 00:21:27.390 position:61%
When a child explores a large image
with a lot of different representations

00:21:27.390 --> 00:21:31.670 position:64%
and a lot that's going on, they sometimes
find it difficult to focus themselves.

00:21:31.670 --> 00:21:36.760 position:67%
So, having and using a tool like crop-it
helps them in a great great way by focusing

00:21:36.760 --> 00:21:40.190 position:70%
in on a particular element of the photograph.

00:21:40.190 --> 00:21:47.350 position:75%
So, let's take an example of this photograph and
we're going to show you the crop-it technique.

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:52.310 position:63%
When you look or you introduce this to a
young learner and it's the Palace Market

00:21:52.310 --> 00:21:59.360 position:69%
in Lincolnville in Saint Augustine, Florida,
1922 to 1927, there's a lot going on.

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:00.960
There are people there.

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:02.730
There's a bicycle there.

00:22:02.730 --> 00:22:05.360
There's a young boy there.

00:22:05.360 --> 00:22:07.080
There's food.

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:11.620
What would you have your
students focus on first?

00:22:11.620 --> 00:22:14.980
Where would you -- as a teacher
or as an administrator --

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:18.000 position:56%
someone working with primary sources
-- what would you focus in on?

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:27.800 position:64%
So, let us show you what we think is an
area that would be a great place to start

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:32.080 position:59%
when you're focusing in on this image.

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:33.020
Good. The boy.

00:22:33.020 --> 00:22:33.640
Excellent.

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:34.630
Julie said the boy.

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:40.490 position:66%
Exactly. And here's an example of what we
would mean by using the crop-it technique.

00:22:40.490 --> 00:22:45.970
So, we've -- we've highlighted the
area out in the back but we boxed

00:22:45.970 --> 00:22:48.430
in the young boy with the bicycle.

00:22:48.430 --> 00:22:50.280
And there are a lot of questions.

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:52.900 position:69%
Let's go back to that term Ilene used before

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:58.350
because we're taking children
beyond just seeing and saying, "OK.

00:22:58.350 --> 00:23:00.120
I see a boy with a basically."

00:23:00.120 --> 00:23:05.750 position:59%
to thinking about -- inquiry, inquiry,
developing thoughtful explanations

00:23:05.750 --> 00:23:12.060 position:67%
to what's going on and asking difficult or
problematic -- or problematizing questions.

00:23:12.060 --> 00:23:14.560
What's he doing with the bicycle?

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:17.740 position:59%
Why is he in the store with a bicycle?

00:23:17.740 --> 00:23:18.570
Who is he?

00:23:18.570 --> 00:23:20.260
What do you think he's going to do?

00:23:20.260 --> 00:23:26.950 position:67%
And getting young children to start here at
this particular point and then expand out.

00:23:26.950 --> 00:23:30.680
Anybody want to guess what they
think he is doing in this picture?

00:23:32.250 --> 00:23:33.910
Excellent, Jamie.

00:23:33.910 --> 00:23:34.770
Delivery boy.

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:40.080 position:69%
Exactly. And that's why he has his bike
filled up with groceries or other materials.

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:40.540
Excellent.

00:23:40.540 --> 00:23:43.660
Very good.

00:23:43.660 --> 00:23:49.590 position:63%
Another area that we want to focus on is
what's called the contextual knowledge.

00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:53.460 position:56%
And this is extremely important when
you're working with primary sources.

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:56.860
OK. We find amazing images
at the Library of Congress

00:23:56.860 --> 00:24:01.050 position:75%
or in our archives and what do you do with them?

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:03.770
What's the background knowledge
that's necessary?

00:24:03.770 --> 00:24:07.000
In this particular case,
we were studying scales.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:11.540 position:61%
But beyond just bringing in the primary
sources, the images of the scale --

00:24:11.540 --> 00:24:14.410
and there's a great image of a
baby being weighed on a scale.

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:18.260 position:66%
They may have seen their brother or sister
in the doctor's office being weighed.

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:22.720 position:72%
There's some larger scales or scales that they
are so old they may not be familiar with them.

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:26.980 position:58%
But what we would like to do then is
to build a contextual knowledge base,

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:32.140 position:67%
a background by bringing in some other
artifacts to build their content knowledge,

00:24:32.140 --> 00:24:35.000 position:64%
to get them thinking or seeing
different representations of information.

00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:46.480 position:69%
&gt;&gt; So, the other thing is that we recognize
is that we can utilize these primary sources

00:24:46.480 --> 00:24:51.290
to help foster young children's
critical thinking skills.

00:24:51.290 --> 00:24:56.060 position:69%
So, I want you all to think about -- I think
our question got a little bit cut off here,

00:24:56.060 --> 00:25:00.250
but the question is, "What can
you catch with a fishing pole?"

00:25:00.250 --> 00:25:04.180 position:70%
So, if you sit there and you kind of think
about in your mind, "What are possible things

00:25:04.180 --> 00:25:05.960 position:63%
that I might catch with a fishing pole?"

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:11.110 position:75%
And if you're a five year old imagining the idea
again, if that's part of your favorite reference

00:25:11.110 --> 00:25:14.350
of having places that you can
go fish and, thanks, Mike, yes!

00:25:14.350 --> 00:25:15.330
Obviously.

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:17.900 position:59%
We can catch fish with a fishing pole.

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:19.930
Well, how about this?

00:25:19.930 --> 00:25:25.210
We can use a fishing pole
to catch a brand new toy.

00:25:25.210 --> 00:25:29.620
So, here we have an image that
helps students begin to think

00:25:29.620 --> 00:25:35.330 position:63%
about that sometimes we can be surprised
by taking what's familiar and part

00:25:35.330 --> 00:25:40.640 position:66%
of our lived experience and now rethinking
about it in a different way and explore

00:25:40.640 --> 00:25:47.890 position:73%
about other ways that tools, resources may have
been used by others as part of their lives.

00:25:47.890 --> 00:25:54.280 position:64%
So we can think about also taking another
context that has some familiar elements

00:25:54.280 --> 00:25:58.380 position:56%
but also has some different things
because of its historical situation.

00:25:58.380 --> 00:26:00.240
So, let's look at this one.

00:26:00.240 --> 00:26:06.420 position:61%
And we might say to children, "So,
what clues in this picture help tell us

00:26:06.420 --> 00:26:10.260 position:61%
about where the event is taking place?"

00:26:10.260 --> 00:26:19.770 position:75%
So, Brian noticed that there's a stove and pots
and pans and Mike also noted about all the pots.

00:26:19.770 --> 00:26:26.080 position:67%
And so, as children, as part of that
visual literacy, what they begin connecting

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:31.260
with is finding representative
data points to justify

00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:35.100
and substantiate the conclusions
that they're drawing.

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:42.400 position:64%
Think about how powerful that is for very
young learners to be able to bring out

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:47.930 position:61%
and read the information they're seeing
as opposed to just looking at it.

00:26:47.930 --> 00:26:49.540 position:61%
Oh, you know, somebody is in a kitchen.

00:26:49.540 --> 00:26:54.530 position:70%
And we could go into harder questions about
what's happening or what's going on in there.

00:26:54.530 --> 00:26:56.840 position:61%
What is she doing in the context there?

00:26:56.840 --> 00:27:00.500
And, actually, in this particular
picture, she's making an apple pie.

00:27:00.500 --> 00:27:04.580
So, it's an interesting dynamic
for children to be able to --

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:10.740 position:69%
and teachers to be able to support students'
critical thinking by introducing these kinds

00:27:10.740 --> 00:27:13.820
of perspectives and orientations.

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:21.760 position:73%
Now, one of the things we also recognize is
that young children typically assess the things

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:29.210 position:69%
that they see visually as sort of the truth
and representations of credible information.

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:36.210 position:61%
And so we need to continue to foster,
again, those inherent sort of questions

00:27:36.210 --> 00:27:40.710
that they begin asking and
instruct them about evaluating

00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:43.850 position:63%
and challenging the information sources.

00:27:43.850 --> 00:27:50.060 position:69%
So, one of those representations of the way
that we might do that in our context, again,

00:27:50.060 --> 00:27:55.150 position:75%
from Florida, is introducing this sort of image.

00:27:55.150 --> 00:27:59.870
So, if we were to introduce this
in a classroom within the context

00:27:59.870 --> 00:28:04.910 position:69%
of our early childhood setting, maybe in the
chat I'd like to hear some of you about some

00:28:04.910 --> 00:28:10.000 position:61%
of the prompts that you might ask young
students about this particular image.

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:16.490
So, how might you focus the
lens of your young students

00:28:16.490 --> 00:28:20.000
to help them read the text
of this particular picture?

00:28:24.350 --> 00:28:26.520
What is Santa doing?

00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:31.500
Lounging out on the beach when you
should be delivering toys to us.

00:28:31.500 --> 00:28:38.950 position:75%
So, how does this young boy seem to be feeling
upon stumbling upon Santa wearing shorts instead

00:28:38.950 --> 00:28:41.900 position:61%
of pants or whatever he might be doing?

00:28:41.900 --> 00:28:44.170
Wondering where is this place.

00:28:44.170 --> 00:28:49.650
And so these are all very important
about fostering students' sense

00:28:49.650 --> 00:28:57.560 position:70%
of critical literacy questions and thinking
about also what kind of skills would you need

00:28:57.560 --> 00:29:04.080 position:59%
to scaffold and help children to
accomplish their thinking and engaging

00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:06.000 position:58%
in this higher level kind of inquiry?

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:15.720 position:69%
So, as you all consider to think about and
contemplate what Santa is doing on the beach

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:20.460
on this particular day and how
this young boy may be reacting

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:24.570 position:56%
to stumbling upon Santa lounging
instead of working away in his shop,

00:29:24.570 --> 00:29:27.930
we're going to go ahead and
transition over to Sue.

00:29:27.930 --> 00:29:28.000
&gt;&gt; Sue.

