00:39:03.500 --> 00:39:07.890 position:72%
We have a few minutes for question and answer.

00:39:07.890 --> 00:39:16.860 position:75%
One of the questions that came through is one
for either of -- either Ilene or Michael Berson.

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:22.430
And that is, "Could you say
more about having students focus

00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:27.510 position:70%
on one particular detail in a primary source?

00:39:27.510 --> 00:39:33.430 position:66%
What's the advantage of having them focus
on a detail whether in crop-it or whatever

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:39.860 position:70%
that you choose and when would you want them
to choose a detail of interest on their own?"

00:39:39.860 --> 00:39:41.690
&gt;&gt; That's a wonderful question.

00:39:41.690 --> 00:39:44.090
Thank you, whomever asked that.

00:39:44.090 --> 00:39:51.090 position:67%
So, part of the process of working with
primary sources with very young learners is

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:59.800 position:59%
to scaffold their skillset and be able
to help them over time develop enhance

00:39:59.800 --> 00:40:05.310 position:58%
and increased visual competencies in
working with the sort of sense making

00:40:05.310 --> 00:40:08.100
that is an inherent skill that
they have, is seeing what they have

00:40:08.100 --> 00:40:10.270 position:63%
but really looking intently, as we said.

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:13.640
It's very intentional movement
from just seeing to looking.

00:40:13.640 --> 00:40:22.060 position:72%
That idea of focusing on a small subset of an
image is really that initial scaffolding step,

00:40:22.060 --> 00:40:25.480
is that we don't want them just
to kind of go all over the place.

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:33.030 position:73%
And quite honestly there can be a lot of
distracting elements that are in a visual image

00:40:33.030 --> 00:40:40.840 position:75%
that may take away from either the core concept
that you're trying to teach or emphasize as part

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:46.070
of your instruction, or just
may create too much information.

00:40:46.070 --> 00:40:52.060 position:75%
So, almost an information overload for the young
learner to be able to optimize their meaning

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:55.860
and active engagement with
that particular element.

00:40:55.860 --> 00:40:59.970
The other thing is that it's sort
of like the interest and fun.

00:40:59.970 --> 00:41:01.660
You know, when we're working
with young learners,

00:41:01.660 --> 00:41:05.320
we always want to be very
playful in our approach.

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:09.840 position:59%
And so this sort of gradual
unveiling of the various little pieces

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:16.420 position:64%
of the puzzle also adds interest and also
helps facilitate their active engagement

00:41:16.420 --> 00:41:18.170
in that process of learning.

00:41:18.170 --> 00:41:22.370
&gt;&gt; Right. We've also explored the
use of some single concept images.

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:27.050 position:64%
And really we've been talking a lot today
about the formal use of primary sources.

00:41:27.050 --> 00:41:29.330 position:61%
So, using crop-it techniques, you know,

00:41:29.330 --> 00:41:33.110
selecting images, focusing
in student's attention.

00:41:33.110 --> 00:41:36.700
But there are single concept
images at the Library of Congress.

00:41:36.700 --> 00:41:38.260
For example, we found a few.

00:41:38.260 --> 00:41:40.330
Children washing their hands.

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:45.590 position:72%
And those can be informally placed in the
classroom where children can specifically look

00:41:45.590 --> 00:41:49.430 position:58%
at a particular concept, washing your
hands, which is something that's done

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:51.720 position:59%
in most classrooms across the country.

00:41:51.720 --> 00:41:57.790 position:70%
So, focusing in on a particular topic through
a crop-it technique or selecting an image

00:41:57.790 --> 00:42:00.900 position:58%
that focuses on a particular concept.

00:42:00.900 --> 00:42:05.720
&gt;&gt; And the question about at what
point do you kind of move or shift

00:42:05.720 --> 00:42:09.750
to students being able to
direct or engage in that.

00:42:09.750 --> 00:42:13.940 position:66%
And that's always about sort of the
readiness and the skillset of the student.

00:42:13.940 --> 00:42:18.440
We are very strong proponents
of a child-centered curriculum.

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:23.230 position:69%
Sort of following the lead of children, what
their areas of interest and inquiry sort

00:42:23.230 --> 00:42:29.770 position:70%
of being the guiding framework is a wonderful
way to mobilize and foster their interests

00:42:29.770 --> 00:42:32.000 position:64%
in looking and exploring and information.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:37.090 position:66%
And one of the things that we also should
mention, you know, for anyone who's worked

00:42:37.090 --> 00:42:42.520 position:66%
with very young children, although there's
been this preponderance of representation

00:42:42.520 --> 00:42:48.490 position:63%
of fictional resources in early learning
classrooms, actually research bears

00:42:48.490 --> 00:42:51.970
out that young children have
a much greater preference

00:42:51.970 --> 00:42:54.960
for authentic representations
of the world around them.

00:42:54.960 --> 00:42:57.250 position:72%
It's the things that they connect with better.

00:42:57.250 --> 00:43:00.770
So, although adults version
of the way children think

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:06.240 position:72%
that they should see the world is
cartoon-like, children actually prefer looking

00:43:06.240 --> 00:43:11.160
at real representations of other
people, places, and the lives

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:13.000 position:58%
and experiences of those around them.

