this question from Bonnie Welsh.

00:43:30.320 --> 00:43:35.030 position:72%
"With young children, is one photograph
enough or is it better to have multiple photos

00:43:35.030 --> 00:43:38.000 position:73%
so the children compare and look more closely?"

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:43.340
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:43:43.340 --> 00:43:49.030 position:75%
That's a great question and when you're starting
to use primary sources in the classroom,

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:57.970
sometimes the inclination is to use
a wide variety of primary sources.

00:43:57.970 --> 00:44:03.110
But I have found in my experience
to start with one source

00:44:03.110 --> 00:44:07.810 position:61%
as kind of launching point for a topic.

00:44:07.810 --> 00:44:13.930 position:66%
As Ilene and Michael mentioned, narrowing
down that information that they are taking

00:44:13.930 --> 00:44:20.750
in to focus on the details that are
important, building that context,

00:44:20.750 --> 00:44:29.360 position:73%
and then bringing in additional primary sources
to build on that prior knowledge over time.

00:44:29.360 --> 00:44:37.270 position:73%
I saw earlier someone mentioned a gallery walk,
setting up a series of images that are focused

00:44:37.270 --> 00:44:47.010 position:73%
on a particular topic, can help students build
their ideas about perspective and understanding

00:44:47.010 --> 00:44:51.510 position:58%
of multiple views on a topic as well.

00:44:51.510 --> 00:44:53.220
But, starting small and building

00:44:53.220 --> 00:44:58.840
from there would be what I would
advise based on my experience.

00:44:58.840 --> 00:45:05.050 position:72%
And I invite Ilene and Michael to add to that.

00:45:05.050 --> 00:45:09.450
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much and, in
